Data for the proposed model mainly involves hydrological data and socio-economic data. All these data (see Table S1-S5 in Supplementary Materials) were obtained from statistical yearbook of Jingmen city, Jingzhou city, and Yichang city, Tuanlin meteorological station, Statistics of Irrigation Accounts in ZRIA, field investigations by Hubei Zhanghe Project Administration Bureau, government reports, and published references (Chen et al., 2017; Cao, 2011; Hou, 2017; Liu, 2018; Jiang, 2020; Yue et al., 2020b). Hydrological data included water supply and crop water demand. Precipitation, reservoir water supply, and external water supply were expressed as TIFNs based on long series statistical data. These data were divided into wet, normal, and dry conditions using frequency analysis method, with the frequencies of 25%, 50%, and 75%, respectively. Crop water demand equaled the value of crop evapotranspiration, which was calculated by multiplying reference evapotranspiration (ET0
                        ) with crop coefficient (Kc
                        ). The Penman-Monteith equation was used to estimate the daily reference evapotranspiration (Allen et al., 1998). And then, reference evapotranspiration in each crop growth stage equaled the cumulative value of daily value.
